1. Create a new project directory: Start by creating a new directory for your TypeScript project. You can use any name you like, but it's recommended to use a name that is descriptive of the project you are working on.
2. Install Node.js and npm: Node.js is the JavaScript runtime environment that powers many of today's web applications, and npm is the package manager used to manage dependencies and packages in Node.js projects. To install Node.js and npm on your system, follow the instructions provided by Node.js on their website.
3. Initialize your project using npm: Once Node.js and npm have been installed, you can initialize your TypeScript project using npm. To do so, navigate to the root directory of your project and run the following command:

```bash
npm init --yes # this will create a "package.json" file for your project
```

This command will create a "package.json" file that contains basic information about your project, such as the name of the package, version, dependencies, and author information.
4. Configure Git for your TypeScript project: Once your TypeScript project has been initialized with npm, you will need to configure Git for your repository. To do so, open up the terminal in the root directory of your project and run the following command:

```bash
git init --quiet # this will initialize a git repository in the current directory
```

This command will initialize a Git repository in the current directory, which is where your TypeScript files will be stored.
5. Add files to your repository: Now that you have initialized Git for your repository, you can start adding files to it by committing them using Git commands. To add a file to your repository, use the following command from within the root directory of your project:

```bash
git add file_name # this will add file_name to the git index
```

This command will add file_name to the index of files that Git needs to track, so it can be committed and pushed to remote repositories later on. Repeat this process for all files that you want to track in your repository.
6. Commit changes: Once you have added all of your files to Git, you can commit them using Git commands. To do so, use the following command from within the root directory of your project:

```bash
git commit -m "message describing changes" # this will create a new commit with message describing changes
```

This command will create a new commit with message describing changes and stage all modified files for inclusion in future commits or pushes. You can also use different commit messages by providing additional arguments when invoking this command. For example:

```bash
git commit -m "message describing changes1" # this will create a new commit with message describing changes1
git commit -m "message describing changes2" # this will create another new commit with message describing changes2
```
